<quiz>
  <question type="stack">
    <name>
      <text>Comparing earthquake magnitudes using logarithms</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>
On a {@day1@} {@time1@}, two earthquakes were recorded in {@region1@} at {@station@}. The first earthquake had magnitude {@m_small@}, and the second had magnitude {@m_large@}.
</p>

<p>
(a) Find the difference in magnitude between the two earthquakes.
</p>

<p>
[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]
</p>

<p>
(b) Using logarithmic principles, determine how many times more powerful the larger earthquake is compared to the smaller one.
</p>

<p>
[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]
</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
Step 1: Find the difference in magnitude:
</p>

<p>
\[
{@m_large@} - {@m_small@} = {@diff@}
\]
</p>

<p>
Step 2: Understand the logarithmic scale.
</p>

<p>
Each increase of 1 in magnitude means the intensity becomes 10 times greater.
</p>

<p>
Step 3: Apply the rule:
</p>

<p>
\[
\text{Intensity ratio} = 10^{@diff@}
\]
</p>

<p>
\[
= {@ratio@}
\]
</p>

<p>
Therefore, the larger earthquake is {@ratio@} times more powerful than the smaller one.
</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
